00:54:14.250 --> 00:54:17.130
MEIR KRYGER: Yeah, so it's a
very tough problem, and one

00:54:17.130 --> 00:54:19.060
of the things you
might consider--

00:54:19.060 --> 00:54:20.560
well, there's two
things to consider

00:54:20.560 --> 00:54:21.643
in that kind of situation.

00:54:21.643 --> 00:54:25.650
Number one is to seek help
from a sleep disorder center

00:54:25.650 --> 00:54:28.390
where they're used to dealing
with this kind of thing.

00:54:28.390 --> 00:54:31.200
And number two-- and
what I advise people--

00:54:31.200 --> 00:54:34.770
is see if you can get
a permanent day job.

00:54:34.770 --> 00:54:40.370
There are some people who
just can't adapt to unusual--

00:54:40.370 --> 00:54:43.710
not unusual-- to schedules
that are not in sync

00:54:43.710 --> 00:54:46.020
with their own circadian clock.

00:54:46.020 --> 00:54:48.720
There are many people
who are night people.

00:54:48.720 --> 00:54:51.180
And for example, if you look
at people in the entertainment

00:54:51.180 --> 00:54:52.320
business--

00:54:52.320 --> 00:54:57.000
these are people who go to bed
2, 3, 4 o'clock in the morning.

00:54:57.000 --> 00:54:57.660
They love it.

00:54:57.660 --> 00:55:00.870
They wake up at 10:00,
11:00 in the morning-- noon.

00:55:00.870 --> 00:55:03.510
And so that's their
natural rhythm.

00:55:03.510 --> 00:55:07.020
So what I advise
people is try to find

00:55:07.020 --> 00:55:11.100
a job that is in sync
with your natural rhythm,

00:55:11.100 --> 00:55:13.140
and you're going to
feel a lot better.

00:55:13.140 --> 00:55:17.280
And depending on your
family's circumstances,

00:55:17.280 --> 00:55:20.910
